{{Infobox person | name = Anatoly Kashpirovsky | image = Кашпировский-Абакан-1 февр 2016-Вики.JPG | image_size = 270px | caption = | birth_name = Anatoliy Mikhailovich Kashpirovskiy | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1939|08|11}} | birth_place = [[Khmelnytskyi, Ukraine|Khmelnytskyi]], [[Ukraine]], [[USSR]] | occupation = Psychotherapist | alma_mater = [[Vinnitsa National Medical University]] | website = [http://www.kashpirovskiy.com/ www.kashpirovskiy.com] }}
'''Anatoly Mikhailovich Kashpirovsky''' ({{lang-uk|Анатолій Михайлович Кашпіровський}}, {{lang-ru|Анато́лий Миха́йлович Кашпиро́вский}}, born 1939) is a [[Russia]]n psychotherapist of Ukrainian origin, hypnotist and a controversial psychic healer who enjoyed great popularity in the Soviet Union. He has recently{{when|date=February 2017}} returned to mass healing in Russia.<ref name="Izvestiya">{{cite web|url=http://www.inedelya.ru/health/article10123 |title=The Shadow of Doctor Kashpirovsky|accessdate=March 26, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323083453/http://www.inedelya.ru/health/article10123 |archivedate=March 23, 2010|language=ru}}</ref>
== Biography == Born in [[Khmelnytskyi, Ukraine]], [[USSR]], Kashpirovsky graduated from the Vinnitskiy Medical Institute in 1962. After this, he worked for 25 years as a [[psychiatrist]] in a psychiatric hospital.
He became famous in 1989 after several of his sessions with patients were shown on Soviet television. Among other things, he was shown to remove the pain of two patients who remained conscious during abdominal surgery by addressing them by teleconferencing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kashpirovskiy.com/ru/main/pages/3772/pg5 |title=Фрагмент из книги "Формула огня" &#124; Анатолий Кашпировский |publisher=Kashpirovskiy.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423083537/http://www.kashpirovskiy.com/ru/main/pages/3772/pg5 |archivedate=2012-04-23 }}</ref> The first session was shown on October 9, 1989 on the Central Channel of the USSR.
In 1993 he was chosen to be a Deputy of the [[Russian Duma]].
