{{Infobox musical artist | name = Glenn Corneille | image = | image_size = | landscape = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank --> | alt = | caption = | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | birth_name = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | alias = | birth_date = {{birth date|1970|07|13}} | birth_place = [[Venlo]], The [[Netherlands]] | origin = | death_date = {{death date and age|2005|08|23|1970|07|13}} | death_place = [[Baarn]], The Netherlands | genre = [[Jazz]] | occupation = Musician | instrument = Piano | years_active = <!-- YYYY–YYYY (or –present) --> | label = | associated_acts = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }} '''Glenn Corneille''' (July 13, 1970 in [[Venlo]] – August 23, 2005 in [[Baarn]]) was a Dutch jazz pianist. He studied at the Conservatory of [[Maastricht]] graduating in 1995 as a teacher. In 2004 he was part of [[Dominique van Hulst]]'s production team.<ref>{{cite web|title=Do Music|url=http://www.domusic.nl/biography.php?language=EN|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>
He played on albums by Boris, Do, Ben Cramer and Alessandro Saffina and was known as one of the pianists in the television programme "De notenclub", which was hosted by Nance and in which Danny Wuyts was the other pianist
Glenn died in a car accident on August 23, 2005<ref>http://www.telegraaf.nl/prive/24522651/Venlose_musicus_Glenn_Corneille_verongelukt.html</ref> and a benefit concert was performed in his honor.
