{{For|Sir Robert Dryden, 3rd Baronet (c. 1638-1708)|Dryden baronets}} '''Robert Dryden''' (February 8, 1917 &ndash; December 16, 2003)<ref>https://www.discogs.com/artist/910361-Robert-Dryden</ref> was an American actor and voice-over performer "whose acting career spanned over four decades of radio, television, theater, and film appearances."<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/01/18/classified/paid-notice-deaths-dryden-robert.html}}</ref>
==Radio== Dryden played Sergeant Maggio in ''Call the Police'',<ref name=rp>Terrace, Vincent (1999). ''Radio Programs, 1924-1984: A Catalog of More Than 1800 Shows''. McFarland & Company, Inc. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-4513-4}}. P. 58.</ref> He also was active on ''[[The FBI in Peace and War]]'',{{r|rp|page1=116}} ''[[The Shadow]]'', ''[[The Fat Man (radio)|The Fat Man]]'', ''[[Big Town]]'', ''[[Gang Busters]]'', ''[[The Adventures of Superman (radio)|The Adventures of Superman]]'', and much later, ''[[CBS Radio Mystery Theater]]''"<ref name=NYT /> and ''[[The General Mills Radio Adventure Theater]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shakespeare's Plays On Mystery Theatre|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2373928/beckley_postherald_the_raleigh_register/|agency=Beckley Post-Herald The Raleigh Register|date=May 7, 1977|page=23|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = May 7, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>
==Television== He appeared in several television programs as well, including ''[[Naked City (TV series)|Naked City]]'', ''[[The Web (TV series)|The Web]]'', ''[[Route 66 (TV series)|Route 66]]'', and ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.
